A longer index than the yearbook is a low risk of cancer
Men who have longer index than the yearbook are exposed to a lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British journal Cancer.
This may depend on the level of hormone male testosterone.
"Our conclusions show that the relative length of the finger is a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men 60 years ago," said the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, professor at the Institute for Research on Cancer at Warwick University.
The finger could thus help determine which men should submit to the prostate cancer test, including by combining with the genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009, she followed with her colleagues in Great Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index of right hand shorter than the yearbook.
For them as for 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those who had the longer index than the yearbook, however, the risk fell by 33 per cent, for men before 60 years the risk reduction reached 87 per cent.
The length report of the two fingers - trained during the prenatal period - indicates, among other things, different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research showed that it is just testosterone that helps develop prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of this study but that it does not seem to him that the relationship between the length of fingers and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
