But above all, France could move forward discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): the issue of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans will not be avoided.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Koscisko-Morizet, who will arrive at Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about the firm start of France and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would be able to increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
Alert to child-injurious pesticides
A 10-year-old child ingested 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published this Wednesday of the Association Generations Futures (ex-The Movement for Rights and Compliance of Future Generations).
The association, which predicts that its results "have no statistically significant value in terms of the small number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem dealt with", bought between July and September the food consumed in four meals and an encas in one day by a child of ten years, in the supermarkets of Oise and Paris.
These types of meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - were examined by laboratories for chemical, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The basis for the assessment is as follows: 81 chemical substances, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable cancers and five listed cancers, as well as 37 substances that can act as endocrine disruptors (PEs), according to studies of several institutions such as the International Research Centre for Cancer.
"Although, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, our investigation shows that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is worrying," notes the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible cancer residues and three averies such as certain cancers as well as close to twenty residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, provided as an index by the study, presents traces of six chemicals, which are still banned by a fungicide in France.
Even for Kenya's green harecots, including in lunch, on which the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the stick hooked, the tuna box, and even the bread bag and the Chewing Gum were hit by pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the most "rich" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic seat used to warm up the food in the microwave was not exempt.
The final risk for the consumer of this "contaminants cocktails" is "probably underestimated", according to the study.
The Alliance of Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), on the other hand, proposed "face to the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to stop "the increase of civilization diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 were in cereals.
